The SPA numbers are questionable at best, and they have roundoff error.  The most
you could hope for is that they got the order of magnitude correct.

And example of this phenomenon.  approximate the first derivative of sin(x) for
x near 1 radian by using (sin(x+delta)-sin(x))/delta, and compare to cos(x).
They SHOULD be identical for sufficiently small delta  (take x~1 radian 
(57 degrees or so), and delta + 0.00001 radian).  THey are not.  This is an 
example of the error.  So now if I have a curve of the approximate 
derivative of sin(x) and I integrate it by adding up all those contributions
from those terms with error... what do I get?  you get sin(x) + error....
That error is a function of how you added your data together how careful you 
were with the original data in the first place, etc.

The SPA has the problem that their data is noisy at best (eg error bars on
each point is a significant fraction of the size of the point), and adding 
up lots of noisy data means that you lose accuracy (unless the noise can
be shown to be random, vs systematic).

The 25-50 million figure you keep harping on Mike is noise.... no more... no
less.  One of the very first things you are ever taught in a numerical
analysis (NA) class is that subtracting 2 very nearly equal numbers gives you 
a number that is not very accurate.  You did that.  NA also teaches you not
to put much faith in such a number.  Unfortunately you did.


